{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ce762257-e506-4603-9591-ef94782bf155","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from your .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file. Copy it out with:\n```sh\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 5. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub), **PerfView**, or convert it to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container image, use the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) sidecar instead — it exposes a REST API for trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- For **host-level** collection (since you have admin), you can also run `PerfView.exe` or `dotnet-counters` on the node to triage before collecting a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"202c9e8d-28ce-46e5-a488-2bdb95fb9b58","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":472,"requestId":"6789:12FCC3:AB51054:BA446D1:69FD3AEF"},"id":"07898dd7-7481-4ec7-934c-8f2572d30417","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:23:06.335Z","parentId":"398e0e88-66ce-47e3-95fc-a9929c832a02"}
